Torneos "admitted to its role in the 15-year scheme, including its role in paying tens of millions of dollars in bribes and kickbacks to a high-ranking Fifa official to secure his support" for broadcast rights to the 2018, 2022, 2026 and 2030 editions of the World Cup," the US Attorney's Office for the eastern district of New York said.Under the arrangement the company won't be prosecuted if it avoids charges in the next four years, pays fines and returns tainted funds.US prosecutors accused 40 officials and marketing executives of soliciting and receiving millions of dollars in bribes in a case that sparked an unprecedented crisis at Fifa.Many have since pleaded guilty in exchange for a possible reduction in sentence.